{{Contains Indic text}}

'''Allahabad''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=Allahabad.ogg|<U+0259>|<U+02C8>|l|<U+0251><U+02D0>|h|<U+0259>|b|<U+0251><U+02D0>|d}}), also known as '''Prayag''' ({{IPAc-en|p|r|<U+0259>|<U+02C8>|y|<U+0251><U+02D0>|g}}), is a city in the [[north India]]n state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and the administrative headquarters of the [[Allahabad District]]. As of 2011, Allahabad is the [[Template:Largest Metropolitan Areas of Uttar Pradesh|seventh most-populous city]] in the state and the [[List of most populous cities in India|thirty-sixth most-populous city]] in India, with an estimated population of 5.11&nbsp;million in the city and 1.21 million in [[Allahabad Metropolitan Area|its metropolitan region]].<ref name="census2011.co.in">{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html |title=Allahabad City Population Census 2011 &#124; Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Census2011.co.in |date= |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/metropolitan/87-allahabad.html |title=Allahabad Metropolitan Urban Region Population 2011 Census |publisher=Census2011.co.in |date= |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref> In 2011, it was ranked the world's 130th fastest-growing city.<ref name="fastest growing">{{cite web|title=The world's fastest growing cities and urban areas from 2006 to 2020|url=http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth2.html|publisher=''City Mayors Statistics''|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.walkthroughindia.com/walkthroughs/10-twin-towns-and-sister-cities-of-indian-states/|title= 10 Twin Towns and Sister Cities of Indian States|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website= walkthroughindia.com|publisher= |accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref>

The city's original name&nbsp;<U+2013> ''Prayaga'', or  "place of offerings"&nbsp;<U+2013> comes from its position at the [[Triveni Sangam|union]] of the [[Ganges]], [[Yamuna]] and [[Sarasvati River]]s. It is the second-oldest city in India, and plays a central role in [[Hindu scriptures]]. Allahabad was originally called Kaushambi (now a [[Kaushambi District|separate district]]) by the Kuru rulers of [[Hastinapur]], who developed it as their capital. Since then, Allahabad has been a political, cultural and administrative centre of the [[Doab]] region. The [[Mughal empire|Mughal]] emperor [[Akbar]] renamed Prayag Allahabad. In 1833 it became the seat of the [[Ceded and Conquered Provinces]] region before its capital was moved to [[Agra]] in 1835.<ref name="MHBI">{{cite book|author=H.S. Bhatia|title=Military History of British India: 1607 <U+2013> 1947|url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=Lrjr7P2HMfkC&pg=PA96&dq=history+of+allahabad&hl=en&sa=X&ei=RsQAU--gGYmCrgeurIBQ&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20allahabad&f=false|accessdate=16 February 2014|publisher=Deep and Deep Publications'|isbn=978-81-8450-079-0|page=97}}</ref> Allahabad became the capital of the [[North-Western Provinces]] in 1858, and was the [[List of capitals of India|capital of India]] for a day.<ref name="Ashutosh Joshi 01-Jan-2008 237">{{cite book |title=Town Planning Regeneration of Cities|author=Ashutosh Joshi|publisher=New India Publishing|date= 1 January 2008|isbn=81-89422-82-0 |page=237 |url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151&dq=Naini&hl=en&sa=X&ei=CN7OUsznI8yTrgeDwYDgCw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwATgU#v=onepage&q=Allahabad%20capital&f=false }}</ref> Allahabad was the capital of the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] from 1902<ref name="Ashutosh Joshi 01-Jan-2008 237"/> to 1920.<ref name="Ward2008">{{cite book|author=Kerry Ward|title=Networks of Empire: Forced Migration in the Dutch East India Company|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=YNBmIu5m6hAC|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Cambridge University Press''|isbn=978-0-521-88586-7|page=340}}</ref>

Located in southern Uttar Pradesh, the city's metropolitan area covers 63.07 km2 (24.35 sq mi). Although the city and its surrounding area are governed by several municipalities, a large portion of Allahabad District is governed by the Allahabad City Council. The city is home to colleges, research institutions and [[Central government|central]] and [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|state government]] offices. Allahabad has hosted cultural and sporting events, including [[Kumbh Mela]] and the [[Indira Marathon]]. Although the city's economy was built on tourism, most of its income now derives from real estate and financial services.

==History==
{{Main|History of Allahabad}}
{{Multiple image
| align     = left
| direction = vertical
| header    =
| header_align = left/right/center
| header_background =
| footer    =
| footer_align = left/right/center
| footer_background =
| width     = 220
| image1    = Fort of Akbar, Allahabad, 1850s.jpg|thumb
| width1    =
| alt1      = Large fort on a busy river
| caption1  =[[Allahabad Fort]], built by Akbar in 1575
| image2    = Gandhi Patel 1940.jpg|thumb
| width2    =
| alt2      = Gandhi seated on a library floor with several other people
| caption2  =[[Mahatma Gandhi]] at a January 1940 [[Congress Working Committee]] meeting with [[Vallabhbhai Patel]] and [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]] at Anand Bhavan in Allahabad
}}
The city was earlier known as Pray<U+0101>ga, a name still commonly used. Pray<U+0101>ga existed during the [[Vedic period]], and is mentioned in the [[Veda]] as the location where [[Brahma]] (the Hindu creator of the universe) attended a ritual sacrifice.<ref name="Dubey2001">{{cite book|author=Shiva Kumar Dubey|title=Kumbh city Prayag|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=DHzXAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Centre for Cultural Resources and Training''|pages=31<U+2013>41}}</ref> Excavations have revealed [[Northern Black Polished Ware]]  dating to 600<U+2013>700 BCE.<ref name="Dubey2001"/> The [[Puranas]] record that [[Yayati]] left Prayag and conquered the region of [[Rigvedic rivers|Saptha Sindhu]].<ref name="Elst2002">{{cite book|author=Koenraad Elst|title=Who is a Hindu?: Hindu revivalist views of Animism, Buddhism, Sikhism, and other offshoots of Hinduism|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=HGPXAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Voice of India''|isbn=978-81-85990-74-3|page=7}}</ref> His five sons ([[Yadu]], [[Druhyu]], [[Puru (Vedic tribe)|Puru]], Anu and [[Turvashas|Turvashu]]) founded the main tribes of the [[Rigveda]].<ref name="Thapar1978">{{cite book|author=Romila Thapar|title=Ancient Indian Social History: Some Interpretations|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=fK3VTUrWsD0C&pg=PA298|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-0808-8|pages=298<U+2013>320}}</ref> [[Lord Rama]], the protagonist of the [[Ramayana]], spent time at the Ashram of Sage Bharadwaj before travelling to nearby Chitrakoot.<ref name="Krishnamoorthy1991">{{cite book|author=K. Krishnamoorthy|title=A Critical Inventory of R<U+0101>m<U+0101>ya<U+1E47>a Studies in the World: Indian languages and English|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iOtreyGBGHQC&pg=PA28|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Sahitya Academy|isbn=978-81-7201-100-0|pages=28<U+2013>51}}</ref>

When the [[Indo-Aryan peoples|Aryans]] first settled in what they called the [[<U+0100>ry<U+0101>varta]] (or Madhyadesha), Prayag (then Kaushambi) was an important part of their territory.<ref name="SmithEdwardes1928">{{cite book|author1=Vincent Arthur Smith|author2=Stephen Meredyth Edwardes|title=The Oxford history of India, from the earliest times to the end of 1911|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=XvRPAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''The Clarendon press''}}</ref> The [[Kuru Kingdom|Kurus]], rulers of Hastinapur (near present day [[Delhi]]), established the town of Kaushambi near Prayag.<ref name="K-M.">{{cite book|title=K-M.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=F1qJNIbbWA0C&pg=PA247|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Sarup & Sons''|isbn=978-81-7625-365-9|page=247}}</ref> They shifted their capital to Kaushambi when [[Hastinapur]] was destroyed by floods.<ref name="SmithEdwardes1928"/>

The Doab region, which includes Allahabad, was controlled by a succession of empires and dynasties.<ref name="Gandhi2007"/> The area became part of the [[Mauryan empire|Mauryan]] and [[Gupta Empire]]s from the east and the [[Kushan Empire]] from the west before being governed by [[Kannauj]] during the 15th century.<ref name="SmithEdwardes1928"/> The city was the site of [[Maratha]] incursions before [[Colonial India|colonial]] rule was imposed on India.<ref name="Gandhi2007">{{cite book|author=Surjit Singh Gandhi|title=History of Sikh Gurus Retold: 1606<U+2013>1708 C.E|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vZFBp89UInUC&pg=PA575|accessdate=20 September 2012|publisher=''Atlantic Publishers & Dist''|isbn=978-81-269-0858-5|page=575}}</ref> In 1765, the British established a garrison at [[Allahabad Fort]]. Prayag became a part of the [[Delhi Sultanate]] when it was annexed by [[Mohammad Ghori]] in 1193.<ref name="KaurSanyal1991">{{cite book|author1=Surinder Kaur|author2=Tapan Kumar Sanyal|title=The Secular Emperor Babar: A victim of Indian partition|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=KEpuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Lokgeet Parkashan''|isbn=978-81-85220-07-9|page=78}}</ref> Later, the Mughals took over from the slave rulers of Delhi and under them Prayag rose to prominence.<ref name="EdwardesGarrett1930">{{cite book|author1=Stephen Meredyth Edwardes|author2=Herbert Leonard Offley Garrett|title=Mughal Rule in India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=4aqU9Zu7mFoC&pg=PA279|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Atlantic Publishers''|isbn=978-81-7156-551-1|pages=279<U+2013>281}}</ref> Allahabad was a provincial capital in the [[Moghul Empire]] under the reign of [[Jahangir]].<ref name="Pletcher 2010 128">{{cite book |last=Pletcher |first=Kenneth |date=15 August 2010 |title=The Geography of India: Sacred and Historic Places |url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=Mjr0X-8jrLAC&pg=PA128&dq=Allahabad+massacre&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_wgsU5Ibw4WsB66ggYgN&ved=0CFgQ6AEwCDgK#v=onepage&q=Allahabad%20massacre&f=false |location= |publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group |page=128 |isbn= |accessdate=21 March 2014 }}</ref> Akbar built a fort on the banks of the [[Triveni sangam|sangam]] and renamed the settlement ''Il<U+0101>h<U+0101>b<U+0101>d'' (Persian for "place of a god") in 1575.<ref name="EdwardesGarrett1930"/>

In 1765, forces of the [[Nawab of Awadh]] and the Mughal emperor [[Shah Alam II]] lost the [[Battle of Buxar]] to the British;<ref name="Andhare1984">{{cite book|author=B. R. Andhare|title=Bundelkhand under the Marathas, 1720<U+2013>1818 A.D.: a study of Maratha-Bundela relations|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=qWYeAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=1<U+2013>2|publisher=''Vishwa Bharati Prakashan''|page=93}}</ref> this was followed by the [[Treaty of Allahabad]]. Although the British did not yet establish direct rule, they saw Allahabad's strategic position and established a garrison in Akbar's fort.<ref name="ThompsonGarratt1999">{{cite book|author1=Edward Thompson|author2=Edward T. & G.T. Garratt|title=History of British Rule in India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=WQFdw9DcmT4C&pg=PA453|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=2|publisher=''Atlantic Publishers''|isbn=978-81-7156-804-8|page=453}}</ref> In 1801, the Nawab of Awadh ceded the city to the [[British East India Company]].<ref name="Martineau1857">{{cite book|author=Harriet Martineau|title=British rule in India: a historical sketch|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rigPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA128|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Smith, Elder and company''|page=128}}</ref> Gradually, the rest of the Doab and its adjoining western region in its west (including Delhi and [[Ajmer-Merwara]]) came under British rule.<ref name="Andhare1984"/> The northwestern area became a new presidency, the [[North-Western Provinces|North Western Provinces of Agra]], with its capital at [[Agra]].<ref name="Andhare1984"/> Allahabad was an important part of the state.<ref name="Basham2008">{{cite book|author=A. L. Basham|title=The Wonder That Was India: A Survey of the Culture of the Indian Sub-Continent Before the Coming of the Muslims|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=6OF-PwAACAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=ACLS History E-Book Project|isbn=978-1-59740-599-7|page=699}}</ref> In 1834, the city became the governmental seat of Agra Province and a High Court was established; a year later, both were moved to Agra.<ref name="Andhare1984"/> Allahabad was a participant in the 1857 [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|Indian Mutiny]],<ref name="Menon2003">{{cite book|author=Visalakshi Menon|title=From Movement To Government: The Congress in the United Provinces, 1937<U+2013>42|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=UO-OxAoL4YIC&pg=PA286|accessdate=25 September 2012|date=9 October 2003|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-9620-0|page=286}}</ref> when [[Maulvi Liaquat Ali]] unfurled the banner of revolt.<ref name="Bose2003">{{cite book|author=Sugata Bose|title=Modern South Asia: History, Culture and Political Economy|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PaKdsF8WzbcC&pg=PA74|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Taylor & Francis''|isbn=978-0-415-30787-1|pages=74<U+2013>77}}</ref> During the rebellion Allahabad, with a number of European troops,<ref name="ThompsonGarratt1962">{{cite book|author1=Edward John Thompson|author2=Geoffrey Theodore Garratt|title=Rise and Fulfilment of British rule in India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=6v4gAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22European+troops%22|accessdate=16 August 2014|publisher=Central Book Depot}}</ref> was the scene of a massacre.<ref name="Pletcher 2010 128"/>

After the mutiny the British established a high court, a police headquarters and a public-service commission in Allahabad,<ref name="SinghSingh1995">{{cite book|author1=Bhai Nahar Singh|author2=Bhai Kirpal Singh|title=Rebels Against the British Rule|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2lu7HatPQCoC&pg=PA290|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Atlantic Publishers & Dist''|isbn=978-81-7156-164-3|page=290}}</ref> making the city an administrative center.<ref name=administrative>{{cite web|title=Civil Disobedience|url=http://www.mkgandhi.org/civil_dis/dandi_march.htm|publisher=Gandhi Research Foundation|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> They truncated the Delhi region of the state, merging it with the [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and moving the capital of the [[North-Western Provinces]] to Allahabad (where it remained for 20 years).<ref name="Ward2008"/> In January 1858, [[Earl Canning]] departed [[Calcutta]] for Allahabad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibiblio.org/britishraj/KayeMalleson4/bk12ch01.html|title=Progress of events in Eastern Bengal, Orisa, Bihar, Oudh, Rohilkhand, and Rajputana |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |website=http://www.ibiblio.org// |publisher= |accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> That year he read [[Queen Victoria#Empress of India|Queen Victoria's proclamation]], transferring control of India from the [[East India Company]] to the [[British Crown]] (beginning the [[British Raj]]), in [[Minto Park, Allahabad|Minto Park]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=FCG5hGZ-hJsC&pg=PA453&dq=minto+park+allahabad&hl=en&sa=X&ei=oFbyUfGIMdHKrAft54BA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=minto%20park%20allahabad&f=false |title=Land and People of Indian States and Union Territories: In 36 Volumes. Uttar ... <U+2013> Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bharatonline.com/uttar-pradesh/travel/allahabad/minto-park.html |title=Minto Park <U+2013> Minto Park Allahabad <U+2013> Allahabad Minto Park <U+2013> Madan Mohan Malaviya Park Allahabad India |publisher=Bharatonline.com |date= |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> In 1877 the provinces of Agra and Awadh were merged to form the [[United Provinces of British India|United Provinces]],<ref name="Basham2008">{{cite book|author=A. L. Basham|title=The Wonder That Was India: A Survey of the Culture of the Indian Sub-Continent Before the Coming of the Muslims|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=6OF-PwAACAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=30 November 2008|publisher=''ACLS History E-Book Project''|isbn=978-1-59740-599-7|page=696}}</ref> with Allahabad its capital until 1920.<ref name="Ward2008">{{cite book|author=Kerry Ward|title=Networks of Empire: Forced Migration in the Dutch East India Company|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=YNBmIu5m6hAC|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Cambridge University Press''|isbn=978-0-521-88586-7|page=340}}</ref>

The 1888 session of the [[Indian National Congress]] was held in the city,<ref name="BhanaPandiri2007">{{cite book|author1=Surendra Bhana|author2=Ananda M. Pandiri|author3=E. S. (FRW) Reddy|author2=Uma Dhupelia-Mesthrie|title=A Comprehensive, Annotated Bibliography on Mahatma Gandhi: Books And Pamphlets About Mahatma Gandhi|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_935ZKVzjW0C&pg=PA12|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Greenwood Publishing Group''|isbn=978-0-313-30217-6|pages=12<U+2013>18}}</ref> and by the turn of the 20th century Allahabad was a revolutionary centre.<ref name="Committee1947">{{cite book|author=Indian National Congress. All India Congress Committee|title=The Allahabad conference of the presidents and secretaries of provincial Congress committees|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=TEU5AQAAIAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Provincial Congress Committee Allahabad''|page=57}}</ref> Nityanand Chatterji became a household name when he hurled a bomb at a European club.<ref name=Independence>{{cite web|title=Besides, locals still pride|url=http://zeenews.india.com/61Independenceday/story.aspx?aid=462215|publisher=''[[Zee News]]''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> In [[Alfred Park]] in 1931, [[Chandrashekhar Azad]] died when surrounded by British police.<ref name="BhawanRana2005">{{cite book | author=Bhawan Singh Rana | title=Chandra Shekhar Azad (An Immortal Revolutionary of India) | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=sudu7qABntcC&pg=PA10 | accessdate=11 September 2012 | date=1 January 2005 | publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd. | isbn=978-81-288-0816-6 | page=10}}</ref> The [[Nehru<U+2013>Gandhi family|Nehru family]] homes, [[Anand Bhavan]] and [[Swaraj Bhavan]], were centers of Indian National Congress activity.<ref name=activities>{{cite web|title=The hub for freedom struggle|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1196506911.html|publisher=''High Beam Research''|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> During the years before independence Allahabad was home to thousands of [[Satyagraha|satyagrahis]] led by [[Purushottam Das Tandon]], [[Bishambhar Nath Pande]], [[Narayan Dutt Tiwari]] and others.<ref name="Desai1986">{{cite book|author=Akshayakumar Ramanlal Desai|title=Violation of Democratic Rights in India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9i5sNMNh_uIC&pg=PA269|accessdate=25 September 2012|year=1986|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-0-86132-130-8|page=269}}</ref> The first seeds of the [[Pakistan]]i nation were sown in Allahabad.<ref name="Zakaria2004">{{cite book|author=Rafiq Zakaria|title=The Man Who Divided India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2RdITXUpyVgC&pg=PA152|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Popular Prakashan''|isbn=978-81-7991-145-7|pages=152<U+2013>158}}</ref> On 29 December 1930, [[Allama Muhammad Iqbal]]'s presidential address to the [[All-India Muslim League]] proposed a separate [[Muslim]] state for the Muslim-majority regions of India.<ref name="Singh2008">{{cite book|author=Upinder Singh|title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=GW5Gx0HSXKUC&pg=PA4|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=''Pearson Education India''|isbn=978-81-317-1677-9|pages=4<U+2013>6}}</ref>

Allahabad is known as the "city of prime ministers" because seven out of 13 prime ministers of India since independence have connections to Allahabad ([[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]], [[Indira Gandhi]], [[Rajiv Gandhi]], [[Gulzarilal Nanda]], [[Vishwanath Pratap Singh]] and [[Chandra Shekhar]]). All seven leaders were either born there, were alumni of [[Allahabad University]] or were elected from an Allahabad constituency.<ref name=prime>{{cite web|title=Prime ministers city|url=http://hardtobelieve.in/primeministers/|publisher=''We''|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>

==Geography==
[[Image:Yamuna river, Allahabad.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=Large waterway, with small boats in the foreground and a long bridge in the background||The [[Yamuna]] in Allahabad during the rainy season]]
Allahabad is in southern Uttar Pradesh, at the confluence of the [[Ganges]] and Yamuna .<ref name=location>{{cite web|title=Location of city|url=http://geography.howstuffworks.com/asia/geography-of-allahabad.htm|publisher=''[[HowStuffWorks]]''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=location001>{{cite web|title=Allahabad Location Guide|url=http://www.weather-forecast.com/locations/Allahabad|work=Weather-forecast|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> The region was known in antiquity first as the Kuru, then as the Vats country.<ref name="Pletcher2010">{{cite book|author=Kenneth Pletcher|title=The History of India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=VsujRFvaHI8C&pg=PA63|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=15 August 2010|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-61530-122-5|page=63}}</ref> To the southwest is [[Bundelkhand]], to the east and southeast is [[Baghelkhand]], to the north and northeast is [[Awadh]] and to the west is the lower [[doab]] (of which Allahabad is part).<ref name=location/> The city is divided by a railway line running east-west.<ref name=junction>{{cite web|title=City or Locality infirmation|url=http://geography.howstuffworks.com/asia/geography-of-allahabad.htm|publisher=''HowStuffWorks''|accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref> South of the railway is the Old Chowk area, and the British-built [[Civil Lines, Allahabad|Civil Lines]] is north of it. Allahabad is geographically and culturally strategically located.<ref name="Ganga-Yamuna Doab">{{cite web|first=Deo Prakash Sharma|title=Archaeology of Lower Ganga-Yamuna Doab|url=http://www.vedicbooks.net/archaeology-lower-gangayamuna-doab-vols-p-997.html|publisher=''Vedic Books''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> Geographically part of the Ganga-Yamuna Doab (at the mouth of the Yamuna), culturally it is the terminus of the Indian west.<ref name="Sharma2006">{{cite book|author=Deo Prakash Sharma|title=Archaeology of lower Ganga-Yamuna Doab (circa 1200 B.C. to 1200 A.D.)|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=EjtuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Bharatiya Kala Prakashan|isbn=978-81-8090-033-4}}</ref> In common with the rest of the doab, its soil and water are primarily [[Alluvium|alluvial]].<ref name=Agricultural>{{cite web|title=Agricultural Productivity and Productivity Regions in Ganga-Yamuna Doab|url=http://www.connectjournals.com/file_full_text/314401H_02-10-21.pdf|publisher=''Bharatiya Kala Prakashan''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> The [[Indian Standard Time]] longitude (25.15<U+00B0>N 82.58<U+00B0>E) is near the city. According to a [[United Nations Development Programme]] report, Allahabad is in a "low damage risk" wind and cyclone zone.<ref name=hazardprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.undp.org.in/dmweb/hazardprofile.pdf|title=Hazard profiles of Indian districts|accessdate=23 August 2006|format=PDF |work=National Capacity Building Project in Disaster Management |publisher=''[[UNDP]]''|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060519100611/http://www.undp.org.in/dmweb/hazardprofile.pdf|archivedate=19 May 2006}}</ref> [[Pratapgarh, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]] is north of the city, [[Bhadohi]] is east, [[Rewa, Madhya Pradesh|Rewa]] is south and [[Kaushambi]] is west.

===Climate===
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Allahabad Climate Graph.gif|left|thumb|alt=Climate timeline| Allahabad climate graph]] -->
Allahabad has a [[humid subtropical climate]] common to cities in the plains of North India, designated ''Cwa'' in the [[K<U+00F6>ppen climate classification]].<ref name="K<U+00F6>ppen">{{cite web|title=Tropical Moist Climates|url=http://www.eoearth.org/article/Tropical_Moist_Climates_-_A_Climate_Type|publisher=''The Encyclopedia of Earth''|accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref> The annual mean temperature is {{Convert|26.1|C|F|abbr=on|1}}; monthly mean temperatures are {{Convert|18|-|29|C|F|abbr=on|0}}.<ref name=weatherbase>
{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=57424&refer=&cityname=Allahabad-Uttar%20Pradesh-India|title=Weatherbase entry for Allahabad|publisher=''Canty and Associates LLC''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Allahabad has three seasons: a hot, dry summer, a cool, dry winter and a warm, humid monsoon. Summer lasts from April to June with temperatures in the low {{Convert|30|C|F|abbr=on|1}}; during dry spells, maximum temperatures often exceed 40&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (104&nbsp;<U+00B0>F) in May and June.<ref name=weatherbase/> The [[monsoon]] begins in early July, and lasts till September. Winter runs from December to February,<ref name=Season/> with temperatures rarely dropping to the freezing point. The daily average maximum temperature is about {{convert|22|C|abbr=on}} and the minimum about {{convert|9|C|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Forecast>{{cite web|title=Weather Report & Forecast|url=http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/allahabad2.htm|publisher=''India Meteorological Department''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> Although Allahabad experiences dense fog in January, resulting in traffic and travel delays,<ref name=Season>{{cite web|title=Allahabad Weather|url=http://www.mustseeindia.com/Allahabad-weather|publisher=''India Weather''|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> the city does not receive snow.<ref name="rainfall & snow"/> Its highest recorded temperature is {{Convert|48|C|F|abbr=on|1}}, and its lowest is {{Convert|-2|C|F|abbr=on|0}}.<ref name=weatherbase/><ref name=climate>{{cite web|title=Allahabad climate|url=http://www.allahabad.climatemps.com/|publisher=''Climate Maps India''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref>

Rain from the Bay of Bengal or the Arabian Sea branches of the [[southwest monsoon]]<ref name=monsoontribune>{{Cite news|last1=Khichar |first1= M. L.|last2= Niwas |first2= R.|title=Know your monsoon|newspaper=''The Tribune''|location= Chandigarh, India|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030714/agro.htm#2|accessdate=9 June 2007}}</ref> falls on Allahabad from June to September, supplying the city with most of its annual rainfall of {{Convert|1027|mm|in|abbr=on|0}}.<ref name="rainfall & snow">{{cite web|title=Average monthly precipitation over the year (rainfall, snow)|url=http://www.weather-and-climate.com/average-monthly-precipitation-Rainfall,Allahabad,India|publisher=''World Weather & Climate Information''|accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref> The highest monthly rainfall total, {{convert|333|mm|in|abbr=on|0}}, occurs in August.<ref name=Tropical>{{cite web|title=Local weather report|url=http://www.tropmet.res.in/~lip/Publication/RR-pdf/RR-119.pdf|publisher=''Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> The city receives 2,961&nbsp;hours of sunshine per year, with maximum [[Insolation|sunlight]] in May.<ref name=climate/>

