===Biodiversity===
[[File:Indian Peacock Plumage.jpg|thumb|alt=Peacock displaying its tail feathers| A typical [[Indian peafowl|Indian peacock]], found in Allahabad on large scale.]]
The Ganga-Jamuna Doab, of which Allahabad is a part, is on the western [[Indus-Gangetic Plain]] region. The doab (including the [[Terai]]) is responsible for the city's unique flora and fauna.<ref name="KalaMuseum2000">{{cite book|author1=Satish Chandra Kala|author2=Allahabad Municipal Museum|title=Flora and fauna in art: particularly in terracottas|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=lP3VAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Allahabad Museum''|page=86}}</ref><ref name="MisraVerma1992">{{cite book|author1=Bal Krishna Misra|author2=Birendra Kumar Verma|title=Flora of Allahabad District, Uttar Pradesh, India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tBq1AAAAIAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Bishen Singh Mahendra Pal Singh Publishing House''|isbn=978-81-211-0077-9|page=530}}</ref> Since the arrival of humans, nearly half of city's [[vertebrate]]s have become extinct. Others are [[endangered]] or have had their range severely reduced. Associated changes in habitat and the introduction of [[reptiles]], [[snakes]] and other [[mammals]] led to the extinction of bird species, including large birds such as [[eagle]]s.<ref name="KalaMuseum2000">{{cite book|author1=Satish Chandra Kala|author2=Allahabad Municipal Museum|title=Flora and fauna in art: particularly in terracottas|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=lP3VAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Allahabad Museum''|pages=22<U+2013>38}}</ref> The [[Allahabad Museum]], one of four national museums in India, is documenting the flora and fauna of the Ganges and Yamuna.<ref name="river belt">{{cite news|title=Allahabad museum to document flora, fauna of Ganga-Yamuna belt|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/allahabad-museum-to-document-flora-fauna-of-gangayamuna-belt/854561/|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=''[[The Indian Express]]''}}</ref>

The most common birds found in the city are [[Columbidae|doves]], [[Peafowl|peacocks]], [[junglefowl]], [[Black Partridge]], [[House Sparrow]]s, [[songbirds]], [[Blue Jay]]s, [[parakeet]]s, [[quail]]s, [[bulbul]]s, and [[Knob-billed Duck|comb duck]]s.<ref name="S.k.agarwal">{{cite book|author=S.K.Agarwal|title=Environment Biotechnology|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0UeDTX6HEK8C&pg=PA61|accessdate=25 July 2012|publisher=''APH Publishing''|isbn=978-81-313-0294-1|pages=61<U+2013>}}</ref> Other animals in the state include reptiles such as [[lizard]]s, [[cobra]]s, [[Bungarus|krait]]s, and [[gharial]]s.<ref name="KalaMuseum2000"/> During winter, large numbers of [[Siberia]]n birds are reported in the [[Triveni sangam|sangam]] and nearby wetlands.<ref name="Siberian birds">{{cite news|last=Aarti|first=Aggarwal|title=Siberian birds flock Sangam, other wetlands|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-02/allahabad/28062841_1_migratory-birds-pond-heron-cattle-egret|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=''[[The Times of India]]''}}</ref>

==Demographics==
{{bar box
|title=Religions in Allahabad<ref name=Composition>{{cite web|title=Religion-wise Composition of Allahabad|url=http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/inner.php?conf=1133|website=http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/|publisher=''All India Radio, Allahabad''|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>
|titlebar=#Fcd116
|left1=Religion
|right1=Percent
|float=right
|bars=
{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|66.81}}
{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|32.72}}
{{bar percent|Others<U+2020>|black|0.47}}
|caption=Distribution of religions<br />
<U+2020><small>Includes [[Sikh]]s (0.13%), [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (<0.04%).</small>
}}

The [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] reported a population of 1,117,094 in Allahabad.<ref name=census>{{cite web|title=Allahabad : Census 2011|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html|publisher=''[[2011 census of India]]''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Provisional data suggest a density of 1,086 people per km<sup>2</sup> in 2011, compared to 901 in 2001.<ref name=census/> Natives of Uttar Pradesh form the majority of Allahabad's population. According to the 2011 census, 66.81 percent of the population were [[Hindu]]s, 32.72 percent were [[Muslim]]s and 0.13 percent were [[Sikh]]s.<ref name=Composition/> The remainder of the population included [[Buddhists]] and followers of other religions; 0.4 percent did not specify a religion.<ref name=1Lakhandabove>{{cite web | url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | format=PDF |page=3 | title=Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011; Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above | publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India | accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> The sex ratio of Allahabad is 858 per 1000 males and child sex ratio of girls is 876 per 1000 boys.<ref name=census/>

Allahabad's literacy rate of 86.50 percent is close to the [[Literacy in India|all-India average]] of 74 percent<ref name="census2011.co.in">{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/138-allahabad.html |title=Allahabad City Population Census 2011 &#124; Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Census2011.co.in |date= |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=censusindliter>{{cite web | url= http://www.census2011.co.in| title= Population census 2011 |publisher= ''Census of India 2011, Government of India''|accessdate= 6 December 2011}}</ref> and the highest in the region.<ref name="literacy rate">{{cite news|title=Allahabad has highest literacy rate in region|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-15/allahabad/29421107_1_literacy-rate-female-population-males|accessdate=3 August 2012|newspaper=''[[The Times of India]]''|date=15 April 2011}}</ref> Male literacy is 90.21 percent and female literacy 82.17 percent.<ref name="census2011.co.in"/><ref name=literacy>{{cite web|title=Average literacy rate of Allahabad|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/questions/546/district-literacy/literacy-rate-of-allahabad-district-2011.html|publisher=''[[Census of India]]''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Among 35 major Indian cities, Allahabad reported the greatest number of violations of special and local laws to the [[NCRB|National Crime Records Bureau]].<ref name=NCRB>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2008/cii-2008/Snapshots.pdf|title=Snaphhots&nbsp;<U+2013> 2008|publisher=''[[National Crime Records Bureau]]''|accessdate=21 October 2010|format=PDF}}</ref>

[[Hindi]], the official state language, is the predominant language in Allahabad. English is also used, particularly by white-collar workers. [[Urdu]] is spoken by a sizable minority.<ref name=1Lakhandabove/> The Hindi dialect spoken in Allahabad is [[Awadhi]], although [[Khariboli]] is also common in the city. [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] are also spoken.<ref name=1Lakhandabove/>

==Civic administration==
{{See also|Neighborhoods in Allahabad}}

[[File:Allahabad high court.jpg|thumb|alt=Large building behind landscaped grounds|The [[Allahabad High Court]] is India's fourth-oldest high court.]]
Allahabad is known as the "Prime Minister Capital of India", since seven of fourteen [[Prime Ministers of India]] are from the city.<ref name=prime/> The city is administered by several [[government agencies]]. The Allahabad Nagar Nigam (ANN), also called Allahabad Municipal Corporation (AMC), oversees the city's civic infrastructure under the Allahabad Metropolitan Region. The corporation originated in 1864, when the Lucknow Municipal Act was passed by the [[Government of India]].<ref name="nagar nigam">{{cite web|title=Nagar Nigam <U+2013> From the casement of history|url=http://allahabadnagarnigam.in/english/about_nagarnigam_allahabad.htm|publisher=''Allahabad Nagar Nigam''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Allahabad is divided into 80 wards, with one member (or corporator) elected from each ward to form the Municipal Committee. The corporators elect the city's mayor.<ref name="nagar nigam"/> Allahabad's chief executive is its Commissioner, who is appointed by the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|state government]]. The city's rapid, unplanned growth has created traffic congestion and stress on infrastructure which has challenged the ANN.<ref name=encourage>{{cite web|title=Nagar Nigam to encourage people's participation|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1081136521.html|publisher=''High Beam Research''|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> Traffic [[gridlock]] has been addressed by a [[Overpass|flyover]] system and one-way streets. Land is expensive in Allahabad, especially in Civil Lines (where skyscrapers exceeding 10<U+2013>15 floors are being built).<ref name="nagar nigam"/>

As of 2012, the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] (BSP) controls the AMC. The city has a non-political [[titular ruler|titular head]], who presides over municipal functions and conferences.<ref name=Checklist>{{cite web|title='Urban Reforms Agenda' under JNNURM|url=http://jnnurm.nic.in/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/Allahabad_MoA1.pdf|publisher=''[[Jawaharlal Nehru National Urban Renewal Mission]]''|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> As the seat of the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]], Allahabad is home to local governing agencies and the [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] (located in the [[Allahabad High Court]] building).<ref name=Checklist/> The Allahabad police, headed by a commissioner, is overseen by the Uttar Pradesh Ministry of Home Affairs. The Allahabad district elects two representatives to India's lower house, the [[Lok Sabha]], and 12 representatives to the state legislative assembly.<ref name=Legislative>{{cite web|title=Bicameral legislature of the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh|url=http://www.uplegassembly.nic.in/16th%20UP%20legislative%20Assembly-Notification.html|publisher=''[[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]''|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>

==Economy==
The primary economic sectors of the district are tourism, fishing and agriculture, and the city is a hub for India's agricultural industry.<ref name="Agricultural industries">{{cite web|title=Agricultural industries in Allahabad|url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/upsdr/vol-2/Chap_b1.pdf|publisher=Planning commission of India|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref><ref name="Main Industries">{{cite web|title=Key industries of Allahabad|url=http://www.districtsofindia.com/uttarpradesh/allahabad/industriesandmining/index.aspx|publisher=District Level Information of Allahabad (Uttar Pradesh)|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> The construction sector is a major part of Allahabad's economy.<ref name="Industrial units">{{cite web|title=Industrial units in allahabad|url=http://uppcb.com/inventory2010/7_allahabad.pdf|publisher=''U.P Pollution Control Board''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> Secondary manufacturers and services may be registered or unregistered;<ref name=development>{{cite web|last=organizations|first=Significant industrial|title=Large scale industries|url=http://www.exploreallahabad.com/economy-of-allahabad|publisher=Explore Allahabad Press|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> according to the third All India Census for Small Scale Industries, there are more than 10,000 unregistered small-scale industries in the city.<ref name="Small scale Industries">{{cite web|title=Summary results of third census|url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/ssiindia/census/sumryres.htm|publisher=''All India Census of Small scale Industries''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="Industries)Industries2004">{{cite book|author=Office of the Development Commissioner (Small Scale Industries)|title=Final results, third all India census of small scale industries, 2001<U+2013>2002|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=LRHtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Development Commissioner, Ministry of Small Scale Industries, Govt. of India''|isbn=978-81-88905-17-1|pages=13<U+2013>18}}</ref> An integrated industrial township has been proposed for {{convert|1200|acre|ha}} in Allahabad by the [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Eastern dedicated freight corridor to get rs 42,000 cr investments to UP |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-17/lucknow/45293731_1_eastern-dedicated-freight-corridor-edfc-amritsar-delhi-kolkata-industrial-corridor |newspaper= The [[Times of India]] |location= |publisher=Swati Mathur |date=17 December 2013 |accessdate= }}</ref>

The city is home to glass- and [[wire]]-based industry.<ref name=industries>{{cite web|title=Minor industries|url=http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-cities-that-will-shape-indias-future/20111012.htm|publisher=''Rediff.com''|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> The main industrial areas of Allahabad are [[Naini]] and [[Phulpur, Allahabad|Phulpur]], where several [[Public sector|public]] and [[private sector]] companies have offices and factories.<ref name="Industries1993">{{cite book|author=Office of the Development Commissioner, Small-Scale Industries, India|title=Report on the second all-India census of small scale industrial units|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9yLtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Development Commissioner, Small Scale Industries, Ministry of Industry, Govt. of India''|page=72}}</ref> [[BPCL|Bharat Petroleum Corporation Limited]], India's largest oil company (which is state-owned), is constructing a seven-million-tonnes-per-annum (MTPA) capacity refinery in Lohgara with an investment estimated at &#8377;62&nbsp;billion.<ref name=GDP>{{cite news|title=GDP & per capita income of Allahabad|url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/upsdr/vol-1/chap%201.pdf|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=''Planning Commission of India''|date=8 March 2010}}</ref> [[Allahabad Bank]], which began operations in 1865,<ref name="Small scale Industries"/> [[Bharat Pumps & Compressors]] and A. H. Wheeler and Company have their headquarters in the city. 

Major companies in Allahabad are [[Reliance Industries]], [[Alstom]], [[ITI Limited]], [[Areva]], [[BPCL]], Dey's Medical, [[Food Corporation of India]], Raymond Synthetics, Triveni Sheet Glass, Triveni Electroplast, EMC, [[Steel Authority of India]], [[HCL Technologies]], [[Indian Farmers Fertiliser Cooperative]] (IFFCO), Vibgyor Laboratories, Geep Industries, Hindustan Cable and GEEP Industries.<ref name=Companies>{{cite web|last=of the city.|first=accelerating the development|title=significant industrial organizations|url=http://www.exploreallahabad.com/economy-of-allahabad|publisher=Explore Allahabad Press|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref name="Popular industries">{{cite web|title=List of Companies|url=http://www.mca.gov.in/Ministry/pdf/Section25_Companies_6nov2008.pdf|publisher=''Ministry of Corporate Affairs''|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> The [[Harish-Chandra Research Institute]] and the Civil Aviation Training Center are also located in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aai.aero/institutes/backdrop_catc.jsp|title=CATC|website=Airports Authority of India|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref><ref name="Popular industries">{{cite web|title=Industries that play a vital role in the economy of the district|url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/uttarpradesh/districts/allahabad.htm|publisher=''Maps of India''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref>

==Culture and tourism==
{{See also|List of tourist attractions in Allahabad}}
[[Image:Anand Bhawan, Allahabad.jpg|thumb|alt=Ornate blue-and-white building, with plaque on a rock in the foreground|[[Anand Bhavan]], owned by Indian political leader [[Motilal Nehru]]]]
Allahabad has a literary and artistic heritage; the former capital the of United Provinces, it was known as Prayag in the [[Vedas]], the ''[[Ramayana]]'' and the ''[[Mahabharata]]''.<ref name="Joshi2008">{{cite book|author=Ashutosh Joshi|title=Town Planning Regeneration of Cities|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151|date=1 January 2008|publisher=New India Publishing|isbn=978-81-89422-82-0|pages=238<U+2013>239}}</ref><ref name=virtue>{{cite web|title=A city of many dimensions is what befits a description of Allahabad |url=http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/allahabad/about.htm|publisher=''Uttar Pradesh Tourism''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> Allahabad has been called the "literary capital of Uttar Pradesh",<ref name=literary>{{cite web|title=Cultural importance of Allahabad|url=http://www.allahabadonline.in/city-guide/culture-of-allahabad|website=http://www.allahabadonline.in/|publisher=Allahabad Online Portal|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> attracting visitors from East Asia;<ref name=Culture>{{cite web|title=Role in Ancient time |url=http://india.mapsofindia.com/destination-guides/culture-of-india/allahabad.html|publisher=''Maps of India''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> the Chinese travellers Huen Tsang and Fa Hien found a flourishing city in the fifth and seventh centuries, respectively.<ref name=HieunTsang>{{cite web|title=Hieun Tsang, sukapha to the treaty of Yandaboo|url=http://www.timesofassam.com/headlines/hiuen-tsang-sukapha-to-the-treaty-of-yandaboo/|publisher=''The Times of Assam'' |accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref> Allahabad remained at the forefront of national importance during the struggle for Indian independence.<ref name="Desai1986"/> The city has a tradition of political graffiti which includes [[Limerick (poetry)|limericks]] and caricatures.<ref name="Committee1947"/>

Allahabad has many buildings featuring [[Indo-Islamic architecture|Indo-Islamic]] and [[Indo-Saracenic architecture]] architecture. Although several buildings from the colonial period have been declared "heritage structures", others are deteriorating.<ref name=Heritage>{{cite web|title=Colonial period buildings in city |url=http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/inner.php?conf=1133 |publisher=''All India Radio, Allahabad''|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> The [[Anand Bhavan]], built during the 1930s as a new home for the [[Nehru<U+2013>Gandhi family|Nehru family]] when the [[Swaraj Bhavan]] became the local [[Indian National Congress]] headquarters, has memorabilia from the Gandhi-Nehru family.<ref name=Palace>{{cite web|title=Swaraj Bhavan|url=http://pages.rediff.com/swaraj-bhavan/1439442 |publisher=''[[Rediff.com]]'' |accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref>
[[File:Kumbh Mela2001.JPG|thumb|alt=Large group of people and vehicles crossing a pontoon bridge|A procession of pilgrims cross the Ganges during the 2001 Kumbh Mela in Allahabad.]]
During the 19th and 20th centuries, [[Hindi literature]] was modernised by authors such as [[Mahadevi Varma]], [[Sumitranandan Pant]], [[Suryakant Tripathi 'Nirala']] and [[Harivansh Rai Bachchan]].<ref name="Gaeffke1978">{{cite book |author=Peter Gaeffke|title=Hindi Literature in the Twentieth Century|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=urN55PYoaSgC&pg=PA3 |accessdate=20 September 2012|year=1978|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-01614-8 |page=3}}</ref> A noted poet was Raghupati Sahay, better known as [[Firaq Gorakhpuri]].<ref name=writer>{{cite web|title=Raghupati Sahay, better known under his pen name Firaq Gorakhpuri |url=http://www.urdupoetry.com/firaq.html |publisher=''Urdu Poetry Archive''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> Gorakhpuri and Varma have received  [[Jnanpith Award]]s.<ref name="Literary Award">{{cite web|title=List of Jnanpith Award Winners|url=http://win2vin.wordpress.com/2009/09/02/list-of-jnanpith-award-winners-indias-highest-literary-award/|publisher=''Word Press''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=winners>{{cite web|title=List of all Bhartiya Jnanpith Award Winners|url=http://win2vin.wordpress.com/2009/09/02/list-of-jnanpith-award-winners-indias-highest-literary-award/|publisher=''UPSC''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=award>{{cite web|title=Jnanpith Award Winners (1965<U+2013>2012)|url=http://currentgk.com/gk/awards/jnanpith_award_winners.html|publisher=Creative Literary|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> Allahabad is a publication centre for Hindi literature, including the Lok Bharti, Rajkamal and Neelabh. [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Urdu literature]] are also studied in the city.<ref name=Literature>{{cite web|title=Urdu and Persian Literature in Allahabad |url=http://www.columbia.edu/itc/mealac/pritchett/00fwp/srf/txt_allahabad.html |publisher=''Columbia Education''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> [[Akbar Allahabadi]] is a noted modern Urdu poet, and Nooh Narwi, Tegh Allahabadi, Shabnam Naqvi and Rashid Allahabadi hail from Allahabad.<ref name=poet>{{cite web|title=Urdu writers and poets of Allahabad|url=http://www.upurduakademi.org/eng/writer.aspx|publisher=''Uttar Pradesh Urdu Academy'' |accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> English author and [[List of Nobel laureates#List of laureates|1907 Nobel laureate]] [[Rudyard Kipling]] was an assistant editor and overseas correspondent for ''[[The Pioneer (newspaper)|The Pioneer]]''.<ref name="nobel">{{cite web |last=Alfred Nobel Foundation|url=http://nobelprize.org/contact/faq/index.html#3b|title=Who is the youngest ever to receive a Nobel Prize, and who is the oldest?|page=409 |publisher=''Nobelprize''|accessdate=30 September 2006 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060925202706/http://nobelprize.org/contact/faq/index.html#3b|archivedate=25 September 2006}}</ref>

Alhough [[Hindu]] women have traditionally worn [[sari]]s, the [[shalwar kameez]] and Western attire is gaining acceptance among younger women.<ref name=dress>{{cite web|last=Rebika|first=Laishram|title=The city have a very rich culture |url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/open-page/article3364929.ece |publisher=''[[The Hindu]]''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> Western dress is worn more by men, although the [[dhoti]] and [[kurta]] are seen during festivals. The formal male [[sherwani]] is often worn with [[chooridar]] on festive occasions.<ref name=dress/> [[Diwali]] (celebrated as a festival of light between mid-October and mid-December) and [[Rama Navami]] (when decorations light the banks of the Ganges and Yamuna) are the two most popular festivals in Allahabad.<ref name="Quick facts">{{cite web|last=Festivals|first=Fairs And|title=The Prayag Tirtha|url=http://www.cultural-heritage-india.com/cities/allahabad.html|publisher=Cultural and Heritage, india|accessdate=12 January 2014}} {{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>

Allahabad is noted for historic, cultural and religious tourism. Historic sites include [[Alfred Park]], the [[Victoria Memorial|Victoria]] and [[Thornhill Mayne Memorial]]s, [[Minto Park]], [[Allahabad Fort]], the [[Allahabad Pillar|Ashoka Pillar]] and [[Khusro Bagh]]. Religious attractions include the [[Kumbh Mela]], the [[Triveni Sangam]] (sacred in [[Shaktism]])<ref>{{cite book |last=  (Translator)|first=  [[Max M<U+00FC>ller|F. Max Muller]]  |authorlink= |title= The Upanishads, Vol I |url= |accessdate= |date= 1 June 2004|publisher=  Kessinger Publishing, LLC |location= | isbn= 1-4191-8641-8|page=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=  (Translator)|first=  [[Max M<U+00FC>ller|F. Max Muller]]  |authorlink= |title= The Upanishads Part II: The Sacred Books of the East Part Fifteen |url= |accessdate= |date= 26 July 2004|publisher= Kessinger Publishing, LLC |location= | isbn= 1-4179-3016-0|page=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kottiyoor Devaswam Temple Administration Portal|url=http://kottiyoordevaswom.com/|work=http://kottiyoordevaswom.com/|publisher=Kottiyoor Devaswam|accessdate=20 July 2013}}</ref> and [[All Saints Cathedral, Allahabad|All Saints Cathedral]]. The city hosts the ''Maha'' [[Kumbh Mela]], the largest religious gathering in the world, every twelve years and the ''Ardh'' (half) Kumbh Mela every six years.<ref name=festival>{{cite web|title=Mythological Significance|url=http://www.indianembassy.org/new/maha_kumbh_mela_2001.htm|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100403014350/http://www.indianembassy.org/new/maha_kumbh_mela_2001.htm|archivedate=3 April 2010|publisher=''[[Embassy of India]]''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=News>{{cite news|title=Pilgrims visiting the Kumbh mela|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kumbh-mela-to-last-for-55-days-instead-of-44-this-year-230857|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=''[[NDTV]]''|date=13 June 2012}}</ref> Cultural attractions include the [[Allahabad Museum]], the [[Jawahar Planetarium]] and the [[University of Allahabad]].

==Transportation==
[[File:Allahabad Airport Terminal.jpg|thumbnail|left|300px|alt=Low building next to a runway|Terminal at Allahabad Airport]]
Allahabad is served by [[Allahabad Airport]] {{Airport codes|IXD|VIAL}}, which began operations in February 1966. The airport is {{convert|12|km}} from the city centre. Air India and Spice Jet connect Allahabad to Delhi and Mumbai.<ref name="Institute1937">{{cite book|author=Allahabad Agricultural Institute|title=The Allahabad aviation |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=4oAsAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=11|publisher=''Allahabad Agricultural Institute, Uttar Pradesh''|page=44}}</ref> Air India began operating a Delhi-Allahabad-Mumbai route on 9 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ashwini Phadnis |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/logistics/air-india-to-begin-new-services-from-sept-9/article5044189.ece |title=Air India to begin new services from Sept 9 &#124; Business Line |publisher=''The Hindu Business Line'' |date=21 August 2013 |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> Other nearby airports are in [[Varanasi]], [[Lucknow]] and [[Kanpur]].<ref name=transport>{{cite web|title=Profile of UP State Unit|url=http://nicsu.up.nic.in/profile.htm|publisher=''National Informatics Centre''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref>

[[Allahabad Junction]] is one of the main railway junctions in northern India and headquarters of the [[North Central Railway Zone]].<ref>{{cite web|title=North Central Railways present network|url=http://www.ncr.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,261|publisher=''[[North Central Railways]]''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> The four major railway stations in Allahabad are Prayag Station, City Station at Rambagh, Daraganj Station and Allahabad Junction.<ref name="Railways (India)">{{cite book|title=Railways (India): return to an order from any correspondence|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yyVDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA30|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1853|pages=30<U+2013>44}}</ref> The city is connected to most other Uttar Pradesh cities and major Indian cities such as [[Jhansi]], [[Kolkata]], New Delhi, [[Mumbai]], [[Visakhapatnam]] [[Chennai]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Indore]], [[Bhopal]], [[Kanpur]], [[Lucknow]] and [[Jaipur]].<ref name="The Railway magazine">{{cite book|title=The Railway magazine|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BCRWAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=124|publisher=''IPC Business Press''|page=178}}</ref> Three-wheeled yellow-and-black [[auto rickshaw]]s, known as ''vikram'', are a popular mode of transportation.<ref name=mode>{{cite web|title=Allahabad Travel|url=http://www.thekumbhmela.com/allahabad-travel-advise.html|publisher=''Kumbh Mela organizing committee''|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> Metered, they can accommodate at least six passengers. Taxis, known as city taxis, are usually available on call. Also metered, they are generally more expensive than auto rickshaws. [[Cycle rickshaw]]s are the most economical means of transportation in Allahabad.<ref name=mode/>

[[File:On the banks of New Yamuna bridge, Allahabad.jpg|thumb|alt=Long bridge, with its lights reflected in the water|[[New Yamuna Bridge, Allahabad|New Yamuna Bridge]], longest [[cable-stayed bridge]] in [[India]]]]
Buses operated by [[Uttar Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation]] (UPSRTC) are an important means of public transport in the city.<ref name="Bus services">{{cite web|title=Important Service|url=http://www.upsrtc.com/allahabad/ald_dep.htm|publisher=''[[Uttar Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation]]''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> [[National Highway 2]] runs through the city centre.<ref name=Status>{{cite web|title=Completed Stretches on NH2|url=http://www.nhai.org/completednh2.htm|publisher=''National Highways Authority of India''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> India's longest [[cable-stayed bridge]], the [[New Yamuna Bridge, Allahabad|New Yamuna Bridge]] (built 2001<U+2013>04), is located in Allahabad and connects the city to the suburb of [[Naini]] across the Yamuna.<ref name=Instrumentation>{{cite web|title=Structural Monitoring System|url=http://www.nhai.org/NIT.htm|publisher=''National Highways Authority of India''|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> The [[Old Naini Bridge]] now accommodates railway and auto traffic.<ref name="Dayaratnam2000">{{cite book|author=P. Dayaratnam|title=Cable Stayed, Supported, and Suspension Bridges|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=pb67nkDk4FMC&pg=PA9|accessdate=25 September 2012|year=2000|publisher=Universities Press|isbn=978-81-7371-271-5|page=9}}</ref><ref name=bridge>{{cite web|title=India's biggest cable-stayed bridge|url=http://www.maurer-soehne.de/files/bauwerkschutzsysteme/pdf/de/projektinfo/PI_NAINI_Bruecke_englisch.pdf|publisher=''Murer Swivel Joist''|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> A road bridge across the Ganges also connects Allahabad and [[Jhusi]].<ref name="Institute1958">{{cite book|title=The Allahabad transportation|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_nghAQAAIAAJ|publisher=''Agricultural Institute,University of Allahabad''|accessdate=3 August 2012|volume=32|page=68}}</ref> Plans for an [[Allahabad Monorail]] are underway. National Waterway 1, operated by the Inland Waterways Authority of India ([[IWAI]]), connects Allahabad and Haldia.

==Education and sports==
{{Main|List of educational institutions in Allahabad}}
[[File:Design Centre MNNIT.jpg|thumb|alt=Palm-tree-lined walkway to two-story building|Design Centre of the [[Motilal Nehru National Institute of Technology Allahabad]], a public engineering and management school]]
The Allahabad educational system is distinct from Uttar Pradesh's other cities, with an emphasis on broad education.<ref name=education>{{cite web|title=Broad education system in city|url=https://www.dasanit.org/docs/DASA-2012-brochure.pdf|publisher=DASA UG|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> The city's's schools are run by the state government and private organisations, many of which are religious. Although English is the language of instruction in most private schools, government schools and colleges offer Hindi and [[English-medium education]].<ref name="Main university">{{cite web|title=Allahabad University|url=http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=141&Itemid=378|publisher=''[[Allahabad University]]''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> Schools in Allahabad follow the [[10+2+3 plan]]. After completing their secondary education, students typically enroll in higher secondary schools affiliated with the [[Uttar Pradesh Board of High School and Intermediate Education]], the [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education|ICSE]] or the [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]].<ref name="Main university"/> and focus on liberal arts, business or science. Vocational programs are also available.<ref name=Vocational>{{cite web|title=Center of Computer Education and Training|url=http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&layout=item&id=78&Itemid=223|publisher=''[[Allahabad University]]''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref>

Allahabad attracts students throughout India. As of 2010, the city had one [[Central University, India|central university]], three [[Deemed university|deemed universities]] and an [[open university]].<ref name="Land Marks">{{cite web|title=University history|url=http://www.allduniv.ac.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=143&Itemid=379|publisher=''[[Allahabad University]]''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> [[Allahabad University]], founded in 1876, is the oldest university in the state.<ref name="Land Marks"/>  [[Motilal Nehru National Institute of Technology Allahabad]] is a noted technical institution.<ref name="Goel2009">{{cite book|author=S.L. Goel Aruna Goel|title=Educational Administration And Management:An Integrated Approach|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=L71yhsLOqtsC&pg=PA94|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Deep & Deep Publications''|isbn=978-81-8450-143-8|page=94}}</ref> Other notable schools in Allahabad include the [[Indian Institute of Information Technology, Allahabad]], [[Motilal Nehru Medical College]] (MNMI), [[Ewing Christian College]] (ECC), the Harish-Chandra Research Institute (HRI), [[Govind Ballabh Pant Social Science Institute]] (GSSI) and the [[Institute of Engineering and Rural Technology]] (IERT).<ref name="GuptaKumar2006">{{cite book|author1=Ameeta Gupta|author2=Ashish Kumar|title=Handbook of Universities|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZKgM7P5iGwgC&pg=PA377|accessdate=4 August 2012|publisher=''Atlantic Publishers''|isbn=978-81-269-0607-9|pages=377<U+2013>379}}</ref>

Academics and artists who were born, worked or studied in Allahabad include mathematician [[Manindra Agrawal]], electrical engineer [[Sorab K. Ghandhi]], poet [[Subhadra Kumari Chauhan]], novelist [[Julia Strachey]], philanthropist [[Jagmal Raja Chauhan]], actor [[Amitabh Bachchan]], Nobel laureate Rudyard Kipling and Lieutenant General [[Syed Ata Hasnain]].

[[Cricket]] and [[Hockey|field hockey]] are the most popular sports in Allahabad,<ref name=Eastern>{{cite web|title=All sporting activities|url=http://www.easternuptourism.com/Allahabad.jsp|publisher=''Eastern Uttar Pradesh Tourism''|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> with [[kabaddi]], [[kho-kho]], [[gilli danda]] and [[pehlwani]] are played in rural areas near the city.<ref name=list>{{cite web|title=List of sports|url=http://www.ncr.indianrailways.gov.in/uploads/files/1326783505969-sportsmeet.pdf|publisher=''North Central Railway''|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> [[Gully cricket]], also known as street cricket, is popular among city youth.<ref name=Eastern/> Several [[sports complex]]es are used by amateur and professional athletes; these include the [[Madan Mohan Malviya Stadium]], the [[Amitabh Bachchan]] Sports Complex and the Boys' High School and College Gymnasium.<ref name="Sports centres">{{cite news|title=City a hub of sports|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-03-02/allahabad/28032289_1_national-sports-academy-indoor-sports-gymnastics|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=''[[The Times of India]]''|date=2 March 2009}}</ref> There is an international-level swimming complex in [[Georgetown, Allahabad|Georgetown]].<ref name=Swimming>{{cite news|title=Quality of sport life-An About-Face|url=http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/97/1205/cs1.html|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=''Asia Now''}}</ref> The National Sports Academy in Jhalwa trains [[gymnasts]] for the [[Commonwealth Games]]. The [[Indira Marathon]] honors the late prime minister [[Indira Gandhi]].<ref name=Marathon>{{cite news|title=Stage set for Indira Marathon|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-16/allahabad/28231200_1_prize-money-prime-minister-prestigious-marathon|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=''[[The Times of India]]''|date=16 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=Athletics>{{cite news|first=Deep|last=Sharad |title=Indira Marathon faces cancellation|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/NM17/Now-Indira-Marathon-faces-cancellation/Article1-159481.aspx|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=''[[Hindustan Times]]''|date=9 October 2006}}</ref><ref name=dominates>{{cite news|last=Vijay Pratap|first=Singh|title=Pune institute dominates Indira Marathon|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/puneinstitutedominatesindiramarathon/388110/|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=''[[The Indian Express]]''|date=20 November 2008}}</ref>

==Media==
Allahabad's Hindi-language newspapers include ''[[Dainik Jagran]]'', ''[[Amar Ujala]]'', ''[[Dainik Bhaskar]]'', ''[[Nai Dunia]]'', ''[[Hindustan Dainik]]'', ''[[Aaj (newspaper)|Aj]]'' and ''[[Rajasthan Patrika]]''.<ref name=newspaper>{{cite web|title= Areawise analysis|url=http://www.indiagrid.com/cgi-bin/news.cgi?dmmy=ok&channel=hindi&mchannel=lang|publisher=''India Grid''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Leader (Allahabad newspaper)|The Leader]]'' and ''[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]]'' are English-language newspapers published in the city;<ref name="The Pioneer">{{cite web|title=History of The Pioneer|url=http://www.itopc.org/travel-requisite/newspapers/pioneer.html|publisher=''Indian Tour Operators Promotion Council''|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=Chintamani>{{cite web|title=English-language newspapers that are produced from city|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000507/spectrum/main2.htm#3|publisher=''[[The Sunday Tribune]]''|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> others include ''[[The Times of India]]'', the ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', ''[[The Hindu]]'', ''[[The Indian Express]]'', and ''[[The Asian Age]]''.<ref name=newspaper/> Newspapers in [[Urdu]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] are also available.

[[All India Radio]], the national, state-owned radio broadcaster, has [[AM broadcasting|AM]] radio stations in the city. Allahabad has five [[Frequency modulation|FM]] stations, including two AIR stations: [[BIG FM 92.7]], [[Red FM 93.5]], [[Gyan Vani]], [[Vividh Bharti]] and Akashwani.<ref name=akashwani>{{cite web|title=All India Radio Allahabad|url=http://www.airallahabad.gov.in/|publisher=All India Radio|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref><ref name="radio stations">{{cite web|title=Radio stations in city|url=http://www.asiawaves.net/india/uttar-pradesh-radio.htm#allahabad-radio|publisher=''Asiawaves''|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> There is a [[Doordarshan]] radio station in the city.<ref name="india radio">{{cite web|title=Doordarshan Kendra, Lajpat Rai Marg, Allahabad|url=http://ddkallahabad.freeservers.com/index.html|publisher=Doordarshan Kendra Allahabad|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> Regional TV channels are accessible via [[Cable television|cable subscription]], [[direct-broadcast satellite]] service or [[IPTV|Internet-based television]].<ref name=regional>{{cite web|title=Present composition of the Prasar Bharati Board|url=http://mib.nic.in/writereaddata/html_en_files/document/docu_other/ar/ar0607/ch4.pdf|publisher=''Broadcasting Corporation of India''|accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>

